Source: OIE Disease Information, Vol. 19 - No. 15 (edited)
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_23.HTM#Sec3>
FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN THE PALESTINIAN AUTONOMOUS TERRITORIES
Immediate notification report
Information received on 9 April 2006 from Dr Imad Mukarker, Deputy
Director General, Veterinary Services and Animal Health, Palestinian
National Authority, Nablus:
Report date: 5 April 2006.
Identification of agent: foot and mouth disease virus type O.
Date of start of the event: 4 February 2006.
Details of outbreaks: In Hebron, there were 3 outbreaks, one in a
farm with 500 cattle in which 10 of 85 cases died. The other two
were in cattle and sheep farms. Outbreaks on sheep farms also
occurred in Jerusalem and Gaza.
Description of affected population:
- The first outbreak in Hebron started in a herd of steers which had
been brought 5 days before the onset of the clinical signs after a
quarantine stay in the quarantine station of Eylat. The herd was
vaccinated during the quarantine but was transported before the end
of the 14-day post-vaccination period to a lamb fattening farm
located just 100 metres far from the steers farm, where the outbreak
started 4 days later. Vaccination in response to the outbreaks: In
Hebron, O, A, Asia 1 were used in cattle and O was used in sheep.
- The outbreak in Jerusalem occurred in an unvaccinated flock.
- The outbreak in Gaza concerns 300 milking sheep bought from Israel
5 days before the onset of clinical signs.
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed: Kimron Veterinary
Institute, Israel
Results: pathogen isolation on cell culture; ELISA; PCR were positive
[Transparency in reporting, such as demonstrated here, is always
important. Thoroughness, accuracy and speed are the hallmarks of
complete transparency.
